      "options": {
        "content": "### 🔬 **Experiment Status & Statistical Analysis**\n\n#### 📊 **Current Sample Sizes**\n- **Adaptive**: ${adaptive_n} interactions\n- **Fixed High**: ${fixed_high_n} interactions\n- **Fixed Mid**: ${fixed_mid_n} interactions\n- **Fixed Low**: ${fixed_low_n} interactions\n\n#### 📈 **Effect Size Analysis**\n- **Mean ΔM Difference**: ${effect_size}\n- **Statistical Significance**: ${significance}\n- **Confidence Level**: ${confidence}\n\n#### 🧪 **Research Interpretation**\n\n${if t_score > 2.5}\n✅ **Strong evidence**: Adaptive significantly outperforms baseline\n${else if t_score > 1.96}\n⚠️ **Weak evidence**: More data needed for definitive conclusions\n${else if sample_size > 10}\n❌ **No significant difference**: Adaptive not better than baseline\n${else}\n🔴 **Insufficient data**: Need n≥30 per group for statistical power\n${end}\n\n#### ⚠️ **Statistical Caveats**\n\n- **Small sample bias**: Results may not generalize\n- **Short-term focus**: Long-term convergence not measured\n- **Variance assumptions**: Normal distribution may not hold\n\n#### 🎯 **Next Research Steps**\n\n1. **Power analysis**: Calculate required n for 80% power\n2. **Longitudinal study**: Track convergence over time\n3. **Effect heterogeneity**: Analyze by user archetype\n4. **Robustness checks**: Non-parametric tests\n\n#### 💡 **Key Scientific Insight**\n\n> **We now have a statistically rigorous framework to answer: \"Does adaptive learning provide measurable benefits over fixed strategies?**\n\nThe experiment is designed for publishable research with proper statistical controls.",
        "mode": "markdown"
      }
